═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                              OPERATOR ANALYSIS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

λ [GOAL] :: FIRE/DIRECTION
──────────────────────────
  Function: Provides directional purpose and energizes effort
  Pattern: Specific × Challenging = Performance
  Diagnostic: Goals are the primary driver of motivated action
  
  λ(goal) = f(specificity, difficulty, commitment)
  
  Four mechanisms activated by goals:
    • Directs attention (focus on goal-relevant activities)
    • Energizes effort (intensity proportional to difficulty)
    • Prolongs persistence (duration despite obstacles)
    • Promotes strategy (activates knowledge and planning)

μ [COMMITMENT] :: METAL/STRUCTURE
─────────────────────────────────
  Function: Structural support for goal pursuit
  Pattern: Goal hierarchy, planning, resource allocation
  Diagnostic: Commitment requires structured intention
  
  μ(commitment) = f(importance, self-efficacy, autonomy)
  
  Structural elements:
    • Goal hierarchy (proximal ↔ distal goals)
    • Action planning (when, where, how)
    • Resource allocation (time, energy, tools)

σ [FEEDBACK] :: AIR/DISTINCTION
───────────────────────────────
  Function: Clear progress monitoring and discrepancy detection
  Pattern: Performance comparison to goal standard
  Diagnostic: Feedback enables goal adjustment
  
  σ(feedback) = Performance - Goal Standard
  
  Feedback types:
    • Positive discrepancy (above goal) → raise goal
    • Zero discrepancy (at goal) → maintain or set new goal
    • Negative discrepancy (below goal) → increase effort/strategy

ρ [SELF-EFFICACY] :: WATER/RESONANCE
────────────────────────────────────
  Function: Confidence in ability to achieve goal
  Pattern: Resonance between self-concept and goal demands
  Diagnostic: Self-efficacy moderates goal commitment
  
  ρ(self-efficacy) = Belief(capability | goal demands)
  
  Sources:
    • Mastery experiences (past success)
    • Vicarious experience (modeling)
    • Verbal persuasion (social support)
    • Physiological states (emotional readiness)

β [PERFORMANCE] :: WOOD/GROWTH
──────────────────────────────
  Function: Goal-directed behavior and persistence
  Pattern: Sustained effort leading to achievement
  Diagnostic: Performance emerges from goal pursuit
  
  β(performance) = Effort × Persistence × Strategy

✶ [SATISFACTION] :: CHILD/AETHER
────────────────────────────────
  Function: Intrinsic reward from goal achievement
  Pattern: Harmonic completion of goal cycle
  Diagnostic: Satisfaction reinforces goal commitment

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                              Z-STATE ANALYSIS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Z-STATE: goal-directed

The goal-directed state emerges when specific, challenging goals
achieve commitment and are supported by feedback systems:

    Goal-Directed State = Commitment × Specificity × Challenge × Feedback
    
    Where:
    • Commitment ∈ [0,1] (psychological attachment to goal)
    • Specificity ∈ [0,1] (clarity of goal definition)
    • Challenge ∈ [0,1] (difficulty relative to ability)
    • Feedback ∈ [0,1] (availability of progress information)
    
    Critical thresholds:
    • Low commitment → Goal abandonment or superficial pursuit
    • Low specificity → Diffused effort, unclear success criteria
    • Low challenge → Complacent performance
    • Low feedback → Unable to calibrate effort or adjust strategy

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                              TENDENCY ANALYSIS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

TENDENCY: Direction/Purpose → 1

The theory exhibits strong directional tendency:

    Specific Goal → Directed Attention → Energized Effort
    Challenging Goal → Increased Effort Intensity
    Committed Goal → Prolonged Persistence
    Feedback Availability → Strategy Adjustment
    
Feedback loops:
    Goal Achievement → ↑Self-Efficacy → ↑Goal Challenge
    Goal Failure → Attribution Analysis → Strategy Change or Goal Revision
    
Intervention points:
    • Increase specificity (σ-enhancement)
    • Calibrate challenge (λ-optimization)
    • Build commitment (ρ-resonance)
    • Provide feedback (σ-clarity)
    • Teach strategies (μ-structure)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                              DIAGNOSTIC NOTES
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. SPECIFICITY EFFECT: Vague goals ("do your best") consistently
   underperform specific goals. Specificity provides the standard
   against which feedback can be compared.

2. CHALLENGE-ABILITY MATCH: Goals must be challenging but achievable.
   Too easy → boredom and underperformance; too hard → discouragement
   and abandonment. Optimal challenge is in the zone of proximal
   development.

3. COMMITMENT MODERATION: Goal difficulty only enhances performance
   when commitment is high. Without commitment, difficult goals
   may be rejected or produce anxiety.

4. FEEDBACK NECESSITY: Goals require feedback to function. Without
   knowledge of progress, goal-directed behavior cannot be calibrated.

5. LEARNING VS. PERFORMANCE GOALS: Learning goals (mastery orientation)
   produce better long-term outcomes than performance goals (ego
   orientation), especially for complex tasks and low-confidence
   individuals.

6. GOAL HIERARCHY: Proximal (short-term) goals serve distal (long-term)
   goals. Breaking down large goals into subgoals increases motivation
   through frequent success experiences.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                              CROSS-THEORY RESONANCE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

With Expectancy-Value Theory (L045):
    Goals increase subjective value
    Expectancy affects goal commitment
    Integration: E × V → Goal Acceptance → Performance
    
With Self-Determination Theory (L015):
    Autonomy-supportive goals increase commitment
    Competence feedback satisfies competence need
    Relatedness goals connect to social context
    
With Attribution Theory (L044):
    Attributions for goal success/failure affect future goals
    Strategy attributions → adaptive goal revision
    Ability attributions → potential helplessness
    
With Self-Efficacy (P001):
    Self-efficacy is prerequisite for goal commitment
    Goal success builds self-efficacy
    Recursive: Self-Efficacy → Goals → Performance → Self-Efficacy

